WEBVTT

00:00.775 --> 00:01.941
[TV static drones]

00:01.941 --> 00:04.877
[bright tone]

00:04.877 --> 00:07.814
<i>[spirited orchestral music]</i>

00:07.814 --> 00:15.019
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:40.403 --> 01:43.643
As you can see, we are
entering into the final phase

01:43.643 --> 01:45.144
of our grand enterprise.

01:45.144 --> 01:46.512
And we're eager
that all of you,

01:46.512 --> 01:48.280
our principal patrons
and sponsors,

01:48.280 --> 01:49.648
should be the first to witness

01:49.648 --> 01:52.017
what the new
Metropolitan Opera will bring

01:52.017 --> 01:53.585
to the great city of New York.

01:53.585 --> 01:56.188
And now, I shall hand you
over to Mr. Gilbert

01:56.188 --> 01:58.157
so he can answer any questions
you may have.

01:58.157 --> 02:00.760
Ladies and gentlemen,
if you'd like to follow me

02:00.760 --> 02:02.228
into the auditorium.

02:02.228 --> 02:05.399
<i>[light music]</i>

02:05.399 --> 02:12.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:12.071 --> 02:14.507
This way.

02:14.507 --> 02:19.311
The work may not be done,
but it is nearly done.

02:19.311 --> 02:23.148
And the first tier where
most of you have taken boxes

02:23.148 --> 02:26.218
needs only
its finishing touches.

02:26.218 --> 02:28.487
[indistinct whispering]

02:28.487 --> 02:31.090
And now, I give you
the grandest opera house

02:31.090 --> 02:33.726
in the world,
the new Metropolitan!

02:33.726 --> 02:37.731
[excited chatter]

02:37.731 --> 02:39.899
My heavens.

02:39.899 --> 02:42.871
[indistinct chatter]

02:45.134 --> 02:48.174
As you can see,
the theater is monumental.

02:48.174 --> 02:50.409
Mrs. Winterton, you came.

02:50.409 --> 02:52.311
Your letter made me curious.

02:52.311 --> 02:54.881
And you're right.
It's very splendid.

02:54.881 --> 02:57.216
Are you thinking
of crossing over to our side?

02:57.216 --> 02:58.884
No, I'm afraid not.

02:58.884 --> 03:01.721
Mr. Winterton values his box
at the Academy so highly,

03:01.721 --> 03:03.857
as you'll understand
better than most.

03:03.857 --> 03:05.557
Mrs. Russell, Mrs. Winterton,
would you mind

03:05.557 --> 03:07.293
holding that pose
for just a second

03:07.293 --> 03:09.962
while our artist makes a sketch
for "The Daily Graphic"?

03:09.962 --> 03:12.498
Not me.
I support the Academy.

03:12.498 --> 03:16.135
- Just you then, Mrs. Russell.
- Of course.

03:16.135 --> 03:17.470
Which box is yours?

03:17.470 --> 03:19.734
Oh, nothing is final yet.

03:19.734 --> 03:21.810
And I'm to believe that?

03:24.645 --> 03:26.312
You're kind
to let me come today

03:26.312 --> 03:28.242
when you know I'll fail you.

03:28.242 --> 03:30.650
That won't stop me
placing temptation in your way.

03:30.650 --> 03:32.218
Is it all
progressing smoothly?

03:32.218 --> 03:33.585
I don't see any workmen.

03:33.585 --> 03:34.921
Oh, they must have
cleared them

03:34.921 --> 03:36.088
for the patrons' visit.
- Ah.

03:36.088 --> 03:37.924
Mrs. Russell,
did you see the item

03:37.924 --> 03:39.659
in a Newport paper recently?

03:39.659 --> 03:41.493
There were no names,
but people say

03:41.493 --> 03:44.496
it was about your son
and a Mrs. Blane.

03:44.496 --> 03:46.232
He seems to be
very fond of her.

03:46.232 --> 03:47.934
We're all fond of Mrs. Blane.

03:47.934 --> 03:49.634
He's starting out
as an architect,

03:49.634 --> 03:52.003
and she has commissioned him
to renovate her house there.

03:52.003 --> 03:54.606
So I suppose they've come
to know each other pretty well.

03:54.606 --> 03:57.343
Yes, we all know
and like Mrs. Blane.

03:57.343 --> 04:00.613
And now I must go.

04:00.613 --> 04:01.514
Oh.

04:01.514 --> 04:03.382
What cheek these people have.

04:03.382 --> 04:05.584
I don't know
where they get their nonsense.

04:05.584 --> 04:07.653
I'm sure there's nothing
to it, but...

04:07.653 --> 04:09.288
But what?

04:09.288 --> 04:11.424
Nothing, really.
I wasn't going to tell you.

04:11.424 --> 04:13.359
It was just that
Maud Beaton made a comment

04:13.359 --> 04:14.826
when we all went
to see that play.

04:14.826 --> 04:17.229
She seemed to think something
was going on between them,

04:17.229 --> 04:18.331
but it was a joke.

04:18.331 --> 04:19.431
Of course it was.

04:19.431 --> 04:22.268
If I could have a word,
Mrs. Russell?

04:22.268 --> 04:25.004
[indistinct chatter]

04:25.004 --> 04:26.867
I'm afraid I have bad news.

04:26.867 --> 04:27.707
Does it have anything to do

04:27.707 --> 04:29.008
with the absence
of any workers?

04:29.008 --> 04:30.043
Precisely.

04:30.043 --> 04:31.811
The money's run out.

04:31.811 --> 04:33.974
We are badly behind
in our schedule

04:33.974 --> 04:35.515
for selling leases
on the boxes.

04:35.515 --> 04:36.682
I'll help with that.

04:36.682 --> 04:39.084
If you can help,
Mrs. Russell, please do,

04:39.084 --> 04:40.220
and don't waste any time.

04:40.220 --> 04:45.992
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:45.992 --> 04:47.392
I hope Miss Ada realizes

04:47.392 --> 04:49.061
that entertaining means
a lot of work.

04:49.061 --> 04:51.064
It's for a good cause.

04:51.064 --> 04:52.431
I think she likes the rector.

04:52.431 --> 04:54.167
Oh, she likes him very much.

04:54.167 --> 04:56.402
And she's earned
a bit of happiness.

04:56.402 --> 04:57.704
How's the clock coming on?

04:57.704 --> 04:59.172
Good, I think.

04:59.172 --> 05:01.073
I'm going to start
testing it this week.

05:01.073 --> 05:03.546
Should we all wear helmets?

05:05.748 --> 05:07.041
Oh.

05:07.041 --> 05:09.048
Bishop Riley has
been a missionary

05:09.048 --> 05:10.850
in Mexico City for years,

05:10.850 --> 05:13.886
saving lives
and sharing the gospel.

05:13.886 --> 05:17.122
So I hope
I've convinced you to join me

05:17.122 --> 05:18.991
in supporting his noble cause.

05:18.991 --> 05:21.827
[applause]

05:21.827 --> 05:22.762
Calm down.

05:22.762 --> 05:24.630
It wasn't
the Gettysburg Address.

05:24.630 --> 05:26.535
What he said was so moving.

05:29.337 --> 05:31.937
The pamphlets on how
you may help the mission

05:31.937 --> 05:34.974
are on the table as you pass
through to the dining room

05:34.974 --> 05:37.644
where we invite you
to join us now for some tea.

05:37.644 --> 05:38.745
Thank you.

05:38.745 --> 05:41.717
[light chatter]

05:44.019 --> 05:45.485
I shouldn't have thought
that this would be

05:45.485 --> 05:47.052
of much interest to you.

05:47.052 --> 05:48.955
I came to support Aunt Ada.

05:48.955 --> 05:50.790
Besides, Miss Beaton is keen

05:50.790 --> 05:52.525
to help spread
the Christian word.

05:52.525 --> 05:54.560
And how does that
sit with you?

05:54.560 --> 05:56.429
I gladly support good causes

05:56.429 --> 05:58.531
from the comfort
of Fifth Avenue.

05:58.531 --> 06:01.200
That bishop sounds
so courageous.

06:01.200 --> 06:02.468
I just wish I were brave enough

06:02.468 --> 06:04.703
to do something practical
to help.

06:04.703 --> 06:07.707
Why don't I make a donation
in your name?

06:07.707 --> 06:08.808
Really?

06:08.808 --> 06:11.044
You continue to surprise me,
Mr. Van Rhijn.

06:11.044 --> 06:14.117
And you continue
to inspire me, Miss Beaton.

06:17.785 --> 06:20.685
I wish I knew
what to make of your cousin.

06:20.685 --> 06:23.488
Well, I've never seen him
like this with anyone.

06:23.488 --> 06:25.359
You bring out the best in him.

06:25.359 --> 06:28.295
And I'm glad.

06:28.295 --> 06:29.328
We should go.

06:29.328 --> 06:30.664
Are you leaving so soon?

06:30.664 --> 06:32.532
I'm afraid
Miss Brook is expected

06:32.532 --> 06:34.134
at my daughter's school tea.

06:34.134 --> 06:35.201
Oh.

06:35.201 --> 06:36.402
Tell Oscar goodbye for me.

06:36.402 --> 06:37.937
Of course.

06:37.937 --> 06:38.938
Shall we?

06:38.938 --> 06:40.406
Well, there's no need
for you to escort me.

06:40.406 --> 06:41.641
I know my way to the school.

06:41.641 --> 06:44.110
It's the least I can do.

06:44.110 --> 06:47.346
Oh, Greece was my favorite
of all the mission trips.

06:47.346 --> 06:50.183
But that was so long ago.

06:50.183 --> 06:51.984
Mm.

06:51.984 --> 06:53.986
Why did you stop?

06:53.986 --> 06:57.156
When my father died,
my mother was alone.

06:57.156 --> 06:59.624
I looked after her
until the end.

06:59.624 --> 07:02.427
Still, you must miss
your missionary work.

07:02.427 --> 07:04.964
If I were counting my regrets,

07:04.964 --> 07:07.632
I would put lack of travel
as number one.

07:07.632 --> 07:09.336
It's not too late
for you to travel.

07:09.336 --> 07:10.469
[laughs]

07:10.469 --> 07:14.773
I shan't argue,
since I hope it's true.

07:14.773 --> 07:20.049
Miss Brook, there's so much
that you can still do.

07:22.884 --> 07:25.785
<i>[gentle music]</i>

07:25.785 --> 07:30.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:30.590 --> 07:34.193
Oh, there you are.

07:34.193 --> 07:35.628
I want to thank both of you

07:35.628 --> 07:37.796
for holding this gathering
for me.

07:37.796 --> 07:40.132
- We were glad to do it.
- Well, you know Ada.

07:40.132 --> 07:44.669
Never happier than when
she's doing good works.

07:44.669 --> 07:47.139
Sure you don't want
anything else to eat?

07:47.139 --> 07:49.641
What about some more tea?

07:49.641 --> 07:51.343
All right, I'll have
another cup of tea.

07:51.343 --> 07:53.279
I see Mrs. Montgomery.
Excuse me.

07:53.279 --> 07:54.981
- Thank you.
- Of course.

07:54.981 --> 07:57.851
Your daughter is charming,
and so old for her age.

07:57.851 --> 07:58.752
She isn't--

07:58.752 --> 08:00.085
And she's just like
her father.

08:00.085 --> 08:02.054
I've watched him
when he comes to collect her.

08:02.054 --> 08:04.657
I must say, you have him
wonderfully trained.

08:04.657 --> 08:06.059
She is like her father, yes.

08:06.059 --> 08:07.794
I don't think we've met,
Mrs. Montgomery.

08:07.794 --> 08:10.496
I'm Mrs. Glennie.
- I'm not Mrs. Montgomery.

08:10.496 --> 08:15.300
I'm Miss Brook,
and I'm Frances's cousin.

08:15.300 --> 08:16.569
I teach here.
- I see.

08:16.569 --> 08:18.365
I do apologize.

08:18.365 --> 08:20.440
Oh, you'll know my daughter,
Sarah Glennie.

08:20.440 --> 08:21.575
Of course.

08:21.575 --> 08:23.175
She's a credit to you.
- Yes.

08:23.175 --> 08:25.511
Well... good.

08:25.511 --> 08:27.550
I'd better see
that she's all right.

08:30.018 --> 08:30.850
There she is.

08:30.850 --> 08:32.419
What were you saying
to Mrs. Glennie?

08:32.419 --> 08:33.552
Nothing much.

08:33.552 --> 08:35.354
Miss Brook,
we're so happy to see you.

08:35.354 --> 08:36.722
- Ah.
- You're our favorite teacher.

08:36.722 --> 08:39.259
Thank you, but let's
keep that to ourselves.

08:39.259 --> 08:42.194
[laughter]

08:42.194 --> 08:43.596
Ah, here's your father.

08:43.596 --> 08:45.398
Am I too early?

08:45.398 --> 08:48.267
No, I think
it's just breaking up now.

08:48.267 --> 08:51.471
You're very kind to have
given Frances your afternoon.

08:51.471 --> 08:52.871
Oh, I've enjoyed it.

08:52.871 --> 08:54.940
It's nice to see all the girls
and their families.

08:54.940 --> 08:58.711
And now, here we are,
the three of us.

08:58.711 --> 09:01.281
Because we make a rather neat
little family too now,

09:01.281 --> 09:02.382
don't we?

09:02.382 --> 09:03.717
Oh.
[laughs]

09:03.717 --> 09:05.919
You mustn't frighten
Miss Brook.

09:05.919 --> 09:08.054
You're not frightened,
are you?

09:08.054 --> 09:09.188
I'm coming!

09:09.188 --> 09:10.855
Of course not.

09:10.855 --> 09:13.692
I've had a lovely time,
but now I should get back.

09:13.692 --> 09:15.360
- The carriage is outside.
- No, I'll walk.

09:15.360 --> 09:17.291
I usually do.
- Nonsense.

09:17.291 --> 09:18.797
No one
in our little family walks,

09:18.797 --> 09:20.867
not when there's a perfectly
good carriage waiting.

09:20.867 --> 09:25.505
She's very grateful,
and so am I.

09:25.505 --> 09:28.677
[girls chattering]

09:30.345 --> 09:33.012
You're not still worried
about that stupid article.

09:33.012 --> 09:36.415
Stupid or not,
we have to be careful.

09:36.415 --> 09:39.352
It was just fizz
for a gossip column.

09:39.352 --> 09:41.053
What does it matter? Ignore it.

09:41.053 --> 09:43.823
You are a bachelor
sowing your wild oats.

09:43.823 --> 09:46.053
You have nothing to lose.

09:46.053 --> 09:50.096
You worry too much.

09:50.096 --> 09:53.132
No one cares.

09:53.132 --> 09:54.837
People care.

09:58.206 --> 10:00.707
What is it?

10:00.707 --> 10:03.509
Your mother has
written to me.

10:03.509 --> 10:08.414
She's asked me to call on her
the next time I'm in New York.

10:08.414 --> 10:09.681
And does she say why?

10:09.681 --> 10:11.718
Well, it seems to be
about getting me to take

10:11.718 --> 10:13.152
a box at the Metropolitan.

10:13.152 --> 10:15.288
Oh, I see.

10:15.288 --> 10:16.455
Yes, it would be.

10:16.455 --> 10:19.225
But why couldn't it wait
until she was back in Newport?

10:19.225 --> 10:21.160
She wouldn't want to wait.

10:21.160 --> 10:24.931
She thinks of nothing else
at the moment.

10:24.931 --> 10:28.200
Will you see her
while you're there?

10:28.200 --> 10:31.738
What reason could I
possibly have for refusing?

10:31.738 --> 10:34.410
Just don't let her worry you.

10:36.444 --> 10:38.710
When will you get
back to Newport?

10:38.710 --> 10:43.315
Thursday, in time
for Mrs. Fish's dinner.

10:43.315 --> 10:45.518
I'll pick you up at 8:00.

10:45.518 --> 10:47.954
Should we arrive together?

10:47.954 --> 10:50.356
I'll drop you at the door,
drive around the block,

10:50.356 --> 10:52.228
and come in later.

10:55.363 --> 10:58.902
And for what it's worth,
I'm not sowing any wild oats...

11:01.336 --> 11:03.072
Because I love you.

11:05.440 --> 11:09.843
And I'm very much afraid
that I love you, Mr. Russell.

11:09.843 --> 11:14.647
Which was not part
of the original plan.

11:14.647 --> 11:17.617
<i>[soft, tense music]</i>

11:17.617 --> 11:24.827
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.929 --> 11:29.396
Are we dining together
this evening?

11:29.396 --> 11:31.230
I don't think so.

11:31.230 --> 11:34.533
That's a pity,
because I have good news.

11:34.533 --> 11:37.336
It's about
the Duke of Buckingham.

11:37.336 --> 11:40.740
I wrote to John Burns,
the English chairman of Cunard.

11:40.740 --> 11:42.909
It seems he knows
the Duke well.

11:42.909 --> 11:44.778
We were invited to a reception.

11:44.778 --> 11:46.378
With the Duke?

11:46.378 --> 11:48.842
Of course, with the Duke.

11:48.842 --> 11:51.117
I said you could fix things
if you put your mind to it.

11:51.117 --> 11:54.120
How was your patrons' tour
of the opera house?

11:54.120 --> 11:55.488
Did it go well?

11:55.488 --> 11:56.656
Not entirely.

11:56.656 --> 11:58.257
We have a problem.

11:58.257 --> 11:59.558
The work stopped.

11:59.558 --> 12:01.027
- Won't they sort it out?
- Maybe.

12:01.027 --> 12:02.394
But the opening
could be delayed

12:02.394 --> 12:03.697
when it's all arranged.

12:03.697 --> 12:05.464
We could even lose our singers.

12:05.464 --> 12:07.634
Do you want me
to look into it?

12:07.634 --> 12:09.768
I'd be grateful if you would.

12:09.768 --> 12:12.239
Apart from that,
did you feel it went well?

12:12.239 --> 12:13.339
I think so,

12:13.339 --> 12:15.708
although Mrs. Winterton took
the chance to rub my face

12:15.708 --> 12:17.076
in her membership
in the Academy.

12:17.076 --> 12:19.946
And a journalist asked me
about some gossip

12:19.946 --> 12:21.881
in a Newport paper,
which some people seem to think

12:21.881 --> 12:23.917
is about Larry and Mrs. Blane.

12:23.917 --> 12:25.785
- What did you say?
- What could I say?

12:25.785 --> 12:27.786
That he's working for her
as her architect?

12:27.786 --> 12:29.756
- Well, that's true.
- It's spreading, George.

12:29.756 --> 12:31.457
It'll be all over New York
before too long.

12:31.457 --> 12:34.093
- You'll control it.
- Is that all I'm good for?

12:34.093 --> 12:36.723
Running around with a blanket
to put out the fires?

12:36.723 --> 12:38.798
Trying to make sure
Larry stays out of trouble,

12:38.798 --> 12:40.466
making sure
Gladys meets the right people.

12:40.466 --> 12:43.136
I cover all your backs,
but who's covering mine?

12:43.136 --> 12:44.904
I hope I am.

12:44.904 --> 12:47.506
That's what I mean to do.
- [sighs]

12:47.506 --> 12:51.178
For me, no one living is
more important than you.

12:51.178 --> 12:52.415
I know.

12:55.250 --> 12:57.083
What do you propose
to do about Larry?

12:57.083 --> 12:59.318
I'm going to talk
to Mrs. Blane.

12:59.318 --> 13:00.687
And what will you say?

13:00.687 --> 13:02.622
Only the truth.

13:02.622 --> 13:04.860
It's usually for the best.

13:09.430 --> 13:11.765
Have you answered
Mr. McNeil's letter yet?

13:11.765 --> 13:14.533
No... and before you ask,

13:14.533 --> 13:17.971
it's because I don't quite know
what that answer should be.

13:17.971 --> 13:20.039
It must be very difficult
for you.

13:20.039 --> 13:23.342
Because I need to be sure
that it's right for her.

13:23.342 --> 13:25.845
Do you think
he'll renege on the terms?

13:25.845 --> 13:27.947
No, he says
that he'll make me comfortable.

13:27.947 --> 13:29.248
I'm sure that he will.

13:29.248 --> 13:32.319
But I need to know
that it's what she wants.

13:32.319 --> 13:33.886
Then tell him.

13:33.886 --> 13:35.822
Write to him and explain

13:35.822 --> 13:38.458
that you need to hear it
from her.

13:38.458 --> 13:40.793
You're right.

13:40.793 --> 13:42.189
I'll do it.

13:42.189 --> 13:43.596
<i>[bright music]</i>

13:43.596 --> 13:44.563
[train whistle blows]

13:44.563 --> 13:46.666
It's an honor to meet you,
Mr. Washington.

13:46.666 --> 13:47.867
My pleasure.

13:47.867 --> 13:49.669
It's quite the journey
from New York.

13:49.669 --> 13:51.203
An important journey.

13:51.203 --> 13:52.839
My wife will be
delighted to have

13:52.839 --> 13:54.073
another lady in the house.

13:54.073 --> 13:55.574
I look forward
to meeting her.

13:55.574 --> 13:57.677
And I can't wait to see
the campus of the dormitory.

13:57.677 --> 13:58.878
- Yes.
- Well, I appreciate

13:58.878 --> 14:00.579
y'all coming down here
to cover this

14:00.579 --> 14:02.114
and give us our time
in the sun.

14:02.114 --> 14:03.616
You deserve a good press.

14:03.616 --> 14:05.150
Oh, I'm gonna
remind you of that

14:05.150 --> 14:06.353
when you're writing
the article.

14:06.353 --> 14:07.220
[laughs]

14:07.220 --> 14:08.855
How did you convince Mr. Porter

14:08.855 --> 14:11.924
to make such a large
contribution?

14:11.924 --> 14:14.093
Barely off the train,
and already at work.

14:14.093 --> 14:17.631
Very good.
[both laugh]

14:17.631 --> 14:18.998
Mr. Thompson.

14:18.998 --> 14:21.534
Mr. Washington,
I hear great things

14:21.534 --> 14:23.002
about your new dormitory.

14:23.002 --> 14:25.270
You should be congratulated.

14:25.270 --> 14:27.143
That's kind of you.
Thank you.

14:30.112 --> 14:31.844
Have things changed
that much in the South

14:31.844 --> 14:33.445
or is it just you?

14:33.445 --> 14:35.948
We're making incremental
changes with the whites

14:35.948 --> 14:38.250
but even bigger changes
for ourselves.

14:38.250 --> 14:40.554
You'll see when we get
to the school.

14:40.554 --> 14:42.989
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:42.989 --> 14:45.258
Would you like to come out
with me and see my father?

14:45.258 --> 14:46.359
I can't.

14:46.359 --> 14:48.027
I'm to meet my aunt in the park
right after school.

14:48.027 --> 14:51.865
We're walking home together.

14:51.865 --> 14:53.433
Miss Brook.

14:53.433 --> 14:54.600
Hello, Miss Barnes.

14:54.600 --> 14:56.602
May I have a word with you?

14:56.602 --> 14:58.071
Of course.

14:58.071 --> 15:00.172
Are you familiar
with Jane Addams?

15:00.172 --> 15:02.407
She's dedicated
to social reform.

15:02.407 --> 15:05.177
We're joining her in starting
some charity classes

15:05.177 --> 15:07.313
for which we need teachers.

15:07.313 --> 15:09.514
I would like you to help
with this cause.

15:09.514 --> 15:11.985
Would I teach painting
at Miss Addams' classes?

15:11.985 --> 15:15.087
No, they need skills
to give them a chance in life.

15:15.087 --> 15:17.222
Reading, writing,
basic arithmetic.

15:17.222 --> 15:19.992
That sort of thing.
- I see.

15:19.992 --> 15:21.494
Thank you for thinking of me.

15:21.494 --> 15:22.829
Of course.

15:22.829 --> 15:28.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:28.468 --> 15:31.571
[indistinct chatter]

15:31.571 --> 15:34.073
You hate peonies.

15:34.073 --> 15:36.676
No. Why would you say that?

15:36.676 --> 15:37.910
[laughs]

15:37.910 --> 15:40.445
I've not given flowers
to many women,

15:40.445 --> 15:44.884
but I don't think
you should be worried.

15:44.884 --> 15:46.753
They're lovely.

15:46.753 --> 15:50.122
But I admit, I do wonder

15:50.122 --> 15:52.424
what Agnes will think.

15:52.424 --> 15:56.296
Those flowers are for you,
Ada Brook.

15:56.296 --> 15:58.030
No one else.

15:58.030 --> 16:00.533
They're very beautiful.

16:00.533 --> 16:03.636
Thank you.

16:03.636 --> 16:05.939
[thunder rumbles]

16:05.939 --> 16:08.208
Oh.
[both laugh]

16:08.208 --> 16:09.675
Yes.

16:09.675 --> 16:13.112
[both laugh]

16:13.112 --> 16:14.614
Right this way, sir.
Right this way.

16:14.614 --> 16:16.015
Oh, thank you.

16:16.015 --> 16:18.452
[thunder rumbling]

16:18.452 --> 16:19.619
Oh, my.

16:19.619 --> 16:21.887
[horse whinnies]

16:21.887 --> 16:23.222
What about Marian?

16:23.222 --> 16:25.058
We can't leave without her.

16:25.058 --> 16:27.893
Well, she won't come here
in the rain.

16:27.893 --> 16:30.597
Why don't we go by the school
to see if she's still there?

16:30.597 --> 16:32.668
Oh, yes.
Let's do that.

16:35.904 --> 16:38.137
[thunder rumbling]

16:38.137 --> 16:39.438
Some gossip has reached me

16:39.438 --> 16:41.806
that I confess
I find disquieting.

16:41.806 --> 16:44.778
I thought I was here to talk
about the new opera house.

16:44.778 --> 16:46.178
That can wait.

16:46.178 --> 16:48.782
Did you see the article?

16:48.782 --> 16:51.584
About you and Larry?

16:51.584 --> 16:54.020
How can you be so sure?
It gave no names.

16:54.020 --> 16:56.188
Don't think I care
what they write about you.

16:56.188 --> 16:58.725
But I do not want them
to connect you with my son.

16:58.725 --> 17:00.559
Larry is working for me.

17:00.559 --> 17:02.762
You've had your fun.
Isn't it time to end it?

17:02.762 --> 17:04.130
What are you talking about?

17:04.130 --> 17:06.833
What is it
that you want from him?

17:06.833 --> 17:09.302
You can't give him an heir.

17:09.302 --> 17:11.437
In 20 years,
when he is in his prime,

17:11.437 --> 17:13.439
you'll be walking with a stick.

17:13.439 --> 17:15.207
Even if he feels
too guilty to leave,

17:15.207 --> 17:17.076
part of him will be
waiting for you to die.

17:17.076 --> 17:18.477
You must remember
what that was like

17:18.477 --> 17:19.879
when you were married
to your husband.

17:19.879 --> 17:21.847
How dare you say such things?

17:21.847 --> 17:22.982
I dare because they're true.

17:22.982 --> 17:24.283
- I'm leaving.
- Very well.

17:24.283 --> 17:26.052
And about the opera--
- I don't care about the opera.

17:26.052 --> 17:27.720
Well, that's good,
because since I wrote,

17:27.720 --> 17:30.022
the boxes have all gone.

17:30.022 --> 17:31.257
So I came here for nothing.

17:31.257 --> 17:32.992
I'm afraid it looks that way.

17:32.992 --> 17:35.962
<i>[light music]</i>

17:35.962 --> 17:43.172
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:45.173 --> 17:46.238
Thank you.

17:46.238 --> 17:49.943
I enjoyed myself,
despite the rain.

17:49.943 --> 17:51.977
I look forward
to our next meeting.

17:51.977 --> 17:54.213
I suppose
that will be Sunday.

17:54.213 --> 17:56.416
Can I see you sooner?

17:56.416 --> 17:58.851
How?

17:58.851 --> 18:00.352
You could come by the church

18:00.352 --> 18:03.522
to discuss
missionary charities.

18:03.522 --> 18:06.926
Or sit with me
for choir rehearsal.

18:06.926 --> 18:09.929
Can you get away
tomorrow evening?

18:09.929 --> 18:11.898
Agnes doesn't
keep me captive.

18:11.898 --> 18:12.999
Good.

18:12.999 --> 18:14.133
I don't think
I have the patience

18:14.133 --> 18:17.069
to wait until Sunday.

18:17.069 --> 18:18.574
Till then.

18:20.842 --> 18:23.743
<i>[bright music]</i>

18:23.743 --> 18:30.753
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.820 --> 18:34.153
Oh.

18:34.153 --> 18:35.988
What happened?

18:35.988 --> 18:37.456
You never came to the park.

18:37.456 --> 18:39.392
The headmistress asked
to speak to me after school,

18:39.392 --> 18:41.393
and by then it was raining,
so I caught a cab.

18:41.393 --> 18:43.729
- Oh.
- Did the rector drop you off?

18:43.729 --> 18:45.197
Yes.

18:45.197 --> 18:46.733
Did he give you those?

18:46.733 --> 18:49.601
He did.

18:49.601 --> 18:52.099
Would you take care
of them for me?

18:52.099 --> 18:54.877
I don't have the strength
to explain them to Agnes.

18:57.178 --> 18:58.814
I better change.

19:03.518 --> 19:04.951
I think it'll be worthwhile.

19:04.951 --> 19:06.547
[sighs]

19:06.547 --> 19:08.287
You must be proud.

19:08.287 --> 19:11.357
It means the headmistress
thinks highly of you.

19:11.357 --> 19:14.293
When does it begin,
teaching these beggars?

19:14.293 --> 19:16.862
Please don't call them that.

19:16.862 --> 19:19.866
I thought tomorrow night,
we might try that lamb receipt

19:19.866 --> 19:21.233
from the "Ladies Home Journal."

19:21.233 --> 19:22.667
I've given it to Mrs. Bauer.

19:22.667 --> 19:25.004
Oh.
Mrs. Wilson's asked me to dine.

19:25.004 --> 19:26.438
The Fanes are going.

19:26.438 --> 19:28.373
I accepted because I thought
you'd be out.

19:28.373 --> 19:29.643
My dinner was canceled.

19:29.643 --> 19:31.009
Mrs. Temple is ill.

19:31.009 --> 19:33.682
I'll have to tell Mrs. Bauer
it will just be the two of us.

19:35.918 --> 19:40.953
Actually, I have plans
for tomorrow evening.

19:40.953 --> 19:42.622
Plans?

19:42.622 --> 19:43.488
What can you mean?

19:43.488 --> 19:44.789
[bee buzzes]
What sort of plans?

19:44.789 --> 19:48.427
I have business
to attend to at the church.

19:48.427 --> 19:51.330
Presumably, this is
the Reverend Mr. Forte again?

19:51.330 --> 19:54.434
He wants to discuss
the missionary charities.

19:54.434 --> 19:56.168
He's working all day,

19:56.168 --> 19:58.004
so he asked me
to come in later.

19:58.004 --> 19:59.605
There's to be a choir practice.

19:59.605 --> 20:01.506
And what will you do
about dinner?

20:01.506 --> 20:03.909
I'm sure he'll see to it
that I don't go hungry.

20:03.909 --> 20:04.911
[bee buzzing]
- Shh. Shh.

20:04.911 --> 20:08.447
- Oh!
- Oh.

20:08.447 --> 20:12.018
Marian thinks you are engaged
in a full-blown flirtation.

20:12.018 --> 20:13.152
What?

20:13.152 --> 20:14.754
You mean with the Reverend,
Mr. Forte?

20:14.754 --> 20:16.956
- Why, are there others?
- Of course not.

20:16.956 --> 20:18.724
I never said that,
Aunt Agnes.

20:18.724 --> 20:19.993
I think you did.

20:19.993 --> 20:21.894
Marian likes
to embroider things

20:21.894 --> 20:23.962
to tease me, to tease us both.

20:23.962 --> 20:26.599
Because it would seem a poor
return after all these years

20:26.599 --> 20:28.234
if you were to desert me now.

20:28.234 --> 20:31.104
Agnes, what has got into you?

20:31.104 --> 20:35.074
So Mr. Forte is nothing?

20:35.074 --> 20:39.745
He is an extremely nice man,
and I like him very much.

20:39.745 --> 20:42.348
That is all I feel for him,
and I am quite sure

20:42.348 --> 20:43.750
it is all he feels for me.

20:43.750 --> 20:45.617
[bee buzzing]
- But if it were more?

20:45.617 --> 20:47.353
If ifs and ands
were pots and pans,

20:47.353 --> 20:48.655
there'd be no need for tinkers.

20:48.655 --> 20:49.588
I'm serious.

20:49.588 --> 20:51.824
I refuse to be serious
about this subject.

20:51.824 --> 20:53.192
[squeal]
Oh!

20:53.192 --> 20:54.961
Bannister, remove the flowers

20:54.961 --> 20:57.797
and the bee that inhabits them.

20:57.797 --> 20:59.635
Where did they come from?

21:04.305 --> 21:06.873
They're mine.

21:06.873 --> 21:07.973
They were a present.

21:07.973 --> 21:10.943
From Cousin Dashiell?

21:10.943 --> 21:14.413
From the parents of a pupil.

21:14.413 --> 21:17.320
Bannister,
we're done with this.

21:19.287 --> 21:21.020
[alarm ringing]

21:21.020 --> 21:24.290
What on Earth is that noise?

21:24.290 --> 21:27.994
I think it may be
my clock alarm.

21:27.994 --> 21:29.128
Telling you what?

21:29.128 --> 21:30.295
That it's time
to clear the plates?

21:30.295 --> 21:33.899
Go and turn it off at once.

21:33.899 --> 21:35.235
I'll fetch the dessert.

21:35.235 --> 21:36.402
Better not.

21:36.402 --> 21:38.607
It might attract more bees.

21:41.576 --> 21:43.375
I'm sorry to summon you here.

21:43.375 --> 21:44.477
I'm rather enjoying it.

21:44.477 --> 21:46.913
It's some time since I've been
in a banker's office.

21:46.913 --> 21:48.915
But I had my own once.

21:48.915 --> 21:50.616
Please.

21:50.616 --> 21:52.552
How many
of your fellow servants know

21:52.552 --> 21:55.187
why you've come here?

21:55.187 --> 21:56.689
Just some
of the senior staff.

21:56.689 --> 21:59.024
The butler, the chef,
the housekeeper.

21:59.024 --> 22:00.426
That's all.

22:00.426 --> 22:02.056
This is exactly
what I cannot have.

22:02.056 --> 22:03.629
The news spreading
through New York

22:03.629 --> 22:05.631
that your father-in-law is
a valet?

22:05.631 --> 22:07.967
I don't expect you
to understand.

22:07.967 --> 22:10.569
But I understand perfectly.

22:10.569 --> 22:12.204
I'm afraid
it won't be possible

22:12.204 --> 22:13.973
for you and Mrs. McNeil
to meet.

22:13.973 --> 22:16.843
She's asked me to speak for her
and to thank you

22:16.843 --> 22:18.310
if you decide
to accept our offer

22:18.310 --> 22:20.279
and move to the West Coast.

22:20.279 --> 22:23.249
I hope that's enough.

22:23.249 --> 22:24.951
No, it's not.

22:24.951 --> 22:26.052
Why not?

22:26.052 --> 22:28.254
Because I must hear it
from her.

22:28.254 --> 22:29.354
I'm sorry.

22:29.354 --> 22:31.257
Do you mean to suggest
that I'm lying?

22:31.257 --> 22:33.059
No.

22:33.059 --> 22:34.526
What else can it be?

22:34.526 --> 22:36.829
I have relayed her wishes.
I have given you her decision.

22:36.829 --> 22:39.132
What other reason can you have
for refusing to believe it?

22:39.132 --> 22:40.500
I am not suggesting anything.

22:40.500 --> 22:41.900
I am not refusing anything.

22:41.900 --> 22:43.970
I am telling you in as polite
and straightforward a manner

22:43.970 --> 22:46.371
as possible
that I won't give up my job

22:46.371 --> 22:48.207
or leave the city
without discussing it

22:48.207 --> 22:51.010
with my daughter.

22:51.010 --> 22:52.578
You're a very stubborn man.

22:52.578 --> 22:54.747
I might say the same.

22:54.747 --> 22:56.481
Very well.

22:56.481 --> 22:58.918
Flora will be very disappointed
that her happiness

22:58.918 --> 23:01.157
is of no concern to you.

23:03.524 --> 23:05.257
I will not answer that
since you know it to be

23:05.257 --> 23:07.426
the very reverse of the truth.

23:07.426 --> 23:10.462
Not just stubborn then,
but also insolent.

23:10.462 --> 23:12.197
If you will forgive me,
Mr. McNeil,

23:12.197 --> 23:15.504
I must be getting back.

23:18.006 --> 23:21.040
<i>[soft music]</i>

23:21.040 --> 23:27.984
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:39.562 --> 23:41.730
[piano notes play]

23:46.402 --> 23:50.136
[piano notes play]

23:50.136 --> 23:52.805
Mrs. Bruce?

23:52.805 --> 23:55.040
What are you doing up here?

23:55.040 --> 23:57.009
Oh, menus, of course.

23:57.009 --> 24:00.240
What else would--

24:00.240 --> 24:04.283
when I was out earlier,
I saw a poster

24:04.283 --> 24:07.052
for a concert in Central Park.

24:07.052 --> 24:08.220
Oh.

24:08.220 --> 24:09.656
What kind of concert?

24:09.656 --> 24:11.257
Well, it was a medley.

24:11.257 --> 24:13.226
Some opera--Verdi, Brahms,

24:13.226 --> 24:15.662
Mendelssohn overture
to "A Midsummer Night's Dream."

24:15.662 --> 24:17.196
That sort of thing.

24:17.196 --> 24:19.999
Um...
[clears throat]

24:19.999 --> 24:22.136
Would you like to go?

24:22.136 --> 24:23.403
What?

24:23.403 --> 24:24.870
Together?

24:24.870 --> 24:29.276
That's--
well, that's the idea.

24:29.276 --> 24:31.544
Yes, I would.

24:31.544 --> 24:34.647
<i>[light music]</i>

24:34.647 --> 24:36.250
You've made me glad.

24:36.250 --> 24:42.922
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:42.922 --> 24:45.691
[door slams]

24:45.691 --> 24:48.031
Mr. Joshua Winterton?

24:51.094 --> 24:52.831
You are good to come.

24:52.831 --> 24:56.035
When Mrs. Astor summons me,
I know what I must do.

24:56.035 --> 24:57.036
[both laugh]

24:57.036 --> 24:59.673
But why was I not
to tell Mrs. Winterton?

24:59.673 --> 25:01.440
Because I wanted you
to tell her

25:01.440 --> 25:02.775
when you know what it's about.

25:02.775 --> 25:05.915
- [chuckles]
- Please.

25:09.451 --> 25:12.646
This is very difficult to say.

25:12.646 --> 25:16.522
But I have lately learned more
of Mrs. Winterton's career,

25:16.522 --> 25:18.824
which leads me to think
that she might not be

25:18.824 --> 25:20.860
entirely happy at the Academy.

25:20.860 --> 25:22.929
Oh, she very much enjoys
the Academy.

25:22.929 --> 25:25.731
Oh, I'm sure
she thinks she does.

25:25.731 --> 25:27.634
But I do not believe
that she will find

25:27.634 --> 25:29.836
the other box holders congenial

25:29.836 --> 25:32.205
when she gets
to know them better.

25:32.205 --> 25:34.005
Why is that?

25:34.005 --> 25:38.378
There is too great a contrast
in her journey through life.

25:38.378 --> 25:40.246
What are you saying?

25:40.246 --> 25:44.117
That Mrs. Winterton is somehow
unsuited to be a box holder?

25:44.117 --> 25:46.519
Are you implying there is
something disreputable

25:46.519 --> 25:47.754
in my wife's past?

25:47.754 --> 25:49.021
Because if you are--

25:49.021 --> 25:51.890
I'm not saying
anything of the sort.

25:51.890 --> 25:55.194
But her history is quite unlike
that of the other ladies

25:55.194 --> 25:57.096
she will meet there.

25:57.096 --> 25:59.666
I don't know
what you're talking about.

25:59.666 --> 26:01.633
Can you be clearer?

26:01.633 --> 26:04.070
That is for Mrs. Winterton
to say.

26:04.070 --> 26:07.741
But in the meantime,
we must surrender our box.

26:07.741 --> 26:08.941
If you don't mind.

26:08.941 --> 26:11.945
But I do mind.
I mind very much.

26:11.945 --> 26:14.414
You know, if we go,
we must transfer

26:14.414 --> 26:15.914
to the new Metropolitan.

26:15.914 --> 26:20.285
And we will take as many
of our old friends as we can.

26:20.285 --> 26:24.623
Even so, that might be best.

26:24.623 --> 26:27.321
And this is
a general decision?

26:27.321 --> 26:30.866
The board has
spoken of it, yes.

26:32.635 --> 26:35.101
Very well.

26:35.101 --> 26:38.871
I cannot fight you when
the blade has already fallen.

26:38.871 --> 26:41.140
But let me give you a warning.

26:41.140 --> 26:44.644
I will not forget this,

26:44.644 --> 26:46.313
and nor will you.

26:46.313 --> 26:48.081
<i>[spirited music]</i>

26:48.081 --> 26:50.284
[sighs]

26:50.284 --> 26:57.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:59.661 --> 27:00.893
He hasn't arrived yet.

27:00.893 --> 27:03.062
- How can you be sure?
- We'll know.

27:03.062 --> 27:05.059
What do we call him
when we meet?

27:05.059 --> 27:07.466
Your Highness? Sir?

27:07.466 --> 27:09.568
Your Grace is
the formal title.

27:09.568 --> 27:11.370
And we're to address him
as Your Grace?

27:11.370 --> 27:12.471
You've got to be kidding.

27:12.471 --> 27:14.674
Mr. McAllister says
that when we meet him socially,

27:14.674 --> 27:17.109
we should just call him Duke.

27:17.109 --> 27:19.445
If the only gain
in our fight for independence

27:19.445 --> 27:20.946
was to dispense
with British titles,

27:20.946 --> 27:22.715
then it was surely worth it.
- [laughs]

27:22.715 --> 27:25.484
Mrs. Russell,
what are you doing here?

27:25.484 --> 27:27.686
Oh, did we need
your permission?

27:27.686 --> 27:30.757
I only meant I wasn't aware
you knew the Duke.

27:30.757 --> 27:32.592
I hear work
on the Metropolitan

27:32.592 --> 27:34.728
has been suspended for a while?

27:34.728 --> 27:36.028
Well, that's been sorted out.

27:36.028 --> 27:38.258
It was a slight hitch,
nothing more.

27:38.258 --> 27:39.198
So it won't upset your plan

27:39.198 --> 27:41.533
to open on the same night
as the Academy?

27:41.533 --> 27:43.703
Good.
I'm looking forward to it.

27:43.703 --> 27:46.142
Me too.
I enjoy competition.

27:50.512 --> 27:52.111
Is that true?

27:52.111 --> 27:54.481
That everything's
back on track with the Met?

27:54.481 --> 27:55.781
Problem solved.

27:55.781 --> 27:57.417
Work will start again
in the morning.

27:57.417 --> 27:59.151
What? How?

27:59.151 --> 28:00.953
I hope you haven't put
your own money into it

28:00.953 --> 28:02.421
when I promised
you wouldn't have to.

28:02.421 --> 28:04.290
No, it was just
bad accounting.

28:04.290 --> 28:06.759
I had Clay look into it,
and it's been sorted out.

28:06.759 --> 28:08.528
[sighs]
That is wonderful.

28:08.528 --> 28:09.796
Thank you.

28:09.796 --> 28:12.732
[door clicks]

28:12.732 --> 28:15.301
Stay here.

28:15.301 --> 28:18.238
[indistinct chatter]

28:18.238 --> 28:25.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:36.457 --> 28:38.525
May I help you, ma'am?

28:38.525 --> 28:42.462
No, thank you.

28:42.462 --> 28:43.863
I'll see you then.

28:43.863 --> 28:45.098
Ladies and gentlemen,

28:45.098 --> 28:47.401
His Grace,
the Duke of Buckingham.

28:47.401 --> 28:54.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:59.881 --> 29:01.413
Your Grace.

29:01.413 --> 29:03.850
Oh, he's much younger
than I thought he'd be.

29:03.850 --> 29:05.184
What were you expecting?

29:05.184 --> 29:07.921
Well, don't most dukes
inherit in late middle age?

29:07.921 --> 29:09.188
I don't know sufficient dukes

29:09.188 --> 29:10.590
to make
a meaningful comparison.

29:10.590 --> 29:12.058
And so you shall.

29:12.058 --> 29:15.261
Do you know...
[indistinct chatter]

29:15.261 --> 29:18.232
<i>[light music]</i>

29:18.232 --> 29:21.461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:21.461 --> 29:22.569
I'll see you
at the table then.

29:22.569 --> 29:24.037
Come.

29:24.037 --> 29:29.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:29.275 --> 29:30.844
I...

29:30.844 --> 29:34.008
[indistinct chatter]

29:34.008 --> 29:41.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:42.156 --> 29:44.424
Excuse me, sir,
I believe your wife

29:44.424 --> 29:46.626
is at the wrong chair.

29:46.626 --> 29:48.060
You're mistaken.

29:48.060 --> 29:51.968
Mrs. Russell is
exactly where she should be.

29:54.803 --> 29:56.570
Ah, Mrs. Russell.

29:56.570 --> 29:57.937
I am pleased.

29:57.937 --> 29:59.806
I've heard all about you
from Mr. Burns.

29:59.806 --> 30:02.979
[indistinct chatter]

30:04.440 --> 30:06.573
I can't be sitting here.

30:06.573 --> 30:08.915
It seems you are,
Mrs. Winterton.

30:08.915 --> 30:12.351
Is that so terrible a fate?

30:12.351 --> 30:14.186
Good gracious, it's you.

30:14.186 --> 30:16.756
Good evening, Mr. Van Rhijn.

30:16.756 --> 30:17.890
I hoped we'd meet again,

30:17.890 --> 30:20.092
but I never thought
it would be like this.

30:20.092 --> 30:22.095
Life is full of surprises.

30:22.095 --> 30:23.563
I'm sorry
if you're disappointed

30:23.563 --> 30:25.164
to find yourself next to me.

30:25.164 --> 30:28.234
It's not that exactly,
but I was told my place was--

30:28.234 --> 30:31.270
[light chatter]

30:31.270 --> 30:33.340
Oh, never mind.
We're here now.

30:33.340 --> 30:34.607
We are.

30:34.607 --> 30:35.975
And you have
till the next course

30:35.975 --> 30:38.344
to describe your ascension.

30:38.344 --> 30:42.248
How did you do it?
I long to hear.

30:42.248 --> 30:44.083
In a way, it's a relief
to be with someone

30:44.083 --> 30:45.818
who knows my whole story.

30:45.818 --> 30:47.720
But first,
is my husband all right?

30:47.720 --> 30:49.055
Who are we looking at?

30:49.055 --> 30:50.823
My husband, Mr. Winterton.

30:50.823 --> 30:53.192
This is Miss Maud Beaton.

30:53.192 --> 30:57.797
Mrs. Winterton, Mr. Winterton
is seated down there.

30:57.797 --> 30:59.933
Next to Lillie Langtry,
the actress.

30:59.933 --> 31:01.534
I met her when I was in London.

31:01.534 --> 31:03.402
She's bound to know the Duke.

31:03.402 --> 31:06.472
She had a long romance
with the Prince of Wales.

31:06.472 --> 31:08.302
I met her
when the Duke entertained us

31:08.302 --> 31:10.009
at Sidmouth Castle.

31:10.009 --> 31:12.278
How do you two
know each other?

31:12.278 --> 31:15.149
We used to be neighbors,
in a way.

31:15.149 --> 31:18.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:18.651 --> 31:21.588
Mm-hmm...

31:21.588 --> 31:23.423
Is something the matter?

31:23.423 --> 31:24.456
[laughs]

31:24.456 --> 31:26.091
It's the way
the Americans lay a table.

31:26.091 --> 31:28.027
I can't get used to it.

31:28.027 --> 31:29.729
Does that make me
sound provincial?

31:29.729 --> 31:30.796
[laughs]

31:30.796 --> 31:32.497
I'm sorry
they didn't get it right.

31:32.497 --> 31:35.067
If I were hosting the dinner,
I can promise you I would.

31:35.067 --> 31:37.069
Is that an invitation,
Mrs. Russell?

31:37.069 --> 31:38.605
Oh, let's see
how tonight goes.

31:38.605 --> 31:40.740
[laughs]

31:40.740 --> 31:43.042
You have a house in Newport,
don't you?

31:43.042 --> 31:44.544
I'm supposed to be
visiting there

31:44.544 --> 31:48.181
to stay... with the Wintertons.

31:48.181 --> 31:49.514
You don't sound
very enthusiastic.

31:49.514 --> 31:52.151
To be honest, I don't know
how I got roped into it.

31:52.151 --> 31:53.614
But I would like
to see the town.

31:53.614 --> 31:55.855
I've heard so much
about the place.

31:55.855 --> 31:58.958
Then why not come
and stay with us instead?

31:58.958 --> 32:01.026
We have two children
not much younger than you.

32:01.026 --> 32:02.429
If only I could.

32:02.429 --> 32:03.763
Of course you can.

32:03.763 --> 32:05.765
The Wintertons won't mind.

32:05.765 --> 32:07.533
I'll give a dinner
and ask them.

32:07.533 --> 32:08.634
They won't be offended.

32:08.634 --> 32:10.335
They'll probably be relieved.

32:10.335 --> 32:13.106
- Do you really think so?
- Absolutely.

32:13.106 --> 32:14.741
Hmm.
[chuckles]

32:14.741 --> 32:18.514
[light chatter]

32:22.450 --> 32:24.583
I find the campus invigorating.

32:24.583 --> 32:27.787
It reminds me of my days at
the Institute in Philadelphia.

32:27.787 --> 32:29.555
All of the young
colored students

32:29.555 --> 32:32.357
working towards their dreams,
whether or not they come true.

32:32.357 --> 32:34.693
It's still
just so full of hope.

32:34.693 --> 32:36.796
That's exactly how you should
describe it in your paper.

32:36.796 --> 32:37.962
[laughter]

32:37.962 --> 32:40.933
It's impressive, I agree,
but we must remain impartial

32:40.933 --> 32:43.168
and not be
unduly influenced by you

32:43.168 --> 32:44.837
or this delicious dinner.

32:44.837 --> 32:45.905
Thank you.

32:45.905 --> 32:48.007
I want to persuade Fannie
to add a cooking class

32:48.007 --> 32:49.074
to our curriculum.

32:49.074 --> 32:51.010
I teach plenty
of useful classes.

32:51.010 --> 32:52.378
Like what?

32:52.378 --> 32:54.113
We have
a dressmaking division now.

32:54.113 --> 32:55.848
The female students
make uniforms

32:55.848 --> 32:57.282
that we actually sell.

32:57.282 --> 32:59.452
It's created a source
of revenue for the school.

32:59.452 --> 33:01.954
And trains the students for
higher paying domestic work,

33:01.954 --> 33:04.223
if they can't get
a teaching job.

33:04.223 --> 33:05.757
I'll show you
while you're here.

33:05.757 --> 33:09.028
Of course, the girls will be
in awe of what you're doing.

33:09.028 --> 33:10.463
In awe because?

33:10.463 --> 33:12.599
That's something they can
never imagine for themselves.

33:12.599 --> 33:14.233
Well, I blush at the idea

33:14.233 --> 33:15.968
that anyone would want
to be me.

33:15.968 --> 33:18.032
[laughter]

33:18.032 --> 33:20.206
I was once at a state dinner
for the Bey of Egypt,

33:20.206 --> 33:22.141
and there was an armed coup
just after the pudding.

33:22.141 --> 33:23.643
You can't be serious.

33:23.643 --> 33:24.944
I certainly am.

33:24.944 --> 33:26.478
All the servants vanished,
and eventually,

33:26.478 --> 33:28.013
I went to look for the cheese
with the wife

33:28.013 --> 33:29.882
of the French ambassador.

33:29.882 --> 33:31.918
And instead,
we were met with bayonets.

33:31.918 --> 33:32.986
Oh, goodness.

33:32.986 --> 33:34.153
Well, I think
it's safe to assume

33:34.153 --> 33:35.488
you'll make it
through tonight's dinner alive.

33:35.488 --> 33:37.422
[chuckles]
Are you willing to promise?

33:37.422 --> 33:39.058
I promise
we'll get past the cheese.

33:39.058 --> 33:40.592
- [laughs]
- She certainly is.

33:40.592 --> 33:43.896
So the pudding's safe, then?
[both laugh]

33:43.896 --> 33:46.098
So what did Aurora
tell you about me?

33:46.098 --> 33:48.367
Just that
your family's complicated,

33:48.367 --> 33:51.270
like every other family I know.

33:51.270 --> 33:53.305
He is using me to do business

33:53.305 --> 33:55.207
and keep his own name
out of it.

33:55.207 --> 33:57.142
Can't you just tell him no?

33:57.142 --> 34:00.713
Could you tell your father no
when he was alive?

34:00.713 --> 34:02.081
I wish I could help.

34:02.081 --> 34:05.254
[light chatter]

34:06.850 --> 34:08.154
Now, I applaud
what you're doing.

34:08.154 --> 34:10.623
But can't you teach them
to fight?

34:10.623 --> 34:13.092
They may gain a degree here,
but in the white world,

34:13.092 --> 34:15.795
these proud students must learn
to creep and crawl

34:15.795 --> 34:17.096
before they're allowed
to exist.

34:17.096 --> 34:19.198
Our lives aren't
so different.

34:19.198 --> 34:20.799
Things may be worse
in the South,

34:20.799 --> 34:23.202
but even in New York,
we enter through the back door.

34:23.202 --> 34:24.904
We're not welcome
in the white stores

34:24.904 --> 34:26.338
or restaurants
or anywhere else.

34:26.338 --> 34:28.140
I've been asked
to make the characters

34:28.140 --> 34:30.309
in my stories white
in order to be published.

34:30.309 --> 34:33.146
Maybe, but you can still earn
a living as a writer.

34:33.146 --> 34:35.514
What is a colored dairy farmer
trained at Tuskegee do

34:35.514 --> 34:37.349
when the white man won't pay
a fair rate?

34:37.349 --> 34:39.284
Why not sell
to a colored man?

34:39.284 --> 34:41.087
Because that man is
probably just a sharecropper

34:41.087 --> 34:42.021
and can't afford it.

34:42.021 --> 34:44.552
Until we demand our rights
as full citizens,

34:44.552 --> 34:45.624
we won't get anywhere.

34:45.624 --> 34:48.994
Of course, I understand
your anger, Mr. Fortune.

34:48.994 --> 34:51.964
Do you think I don't feel it?

34:51.964 --> 34:54.400
But it doesn't work down here.

34:54.400 --> 34:56.668
To build Tuskegee
into what it is now,

34:56.668 --> 34:59.338
I have had to make peace
with the white folk.

34:59.338 --> 35:01.707
The white men terrorize
colored folks in these parts,

35:01.707 --> 35:02.809
and no one does anything.

35:02.809 --> 35:04.243
I'm not making deals

35:04.243 --> 35:06.345
with the white people
who terrorize us.

35:06.345 --> 35:07.614
How can you tell
the difference?

35:07.614 --> 35:09.585
[scoffs]

35:11.586 --> 35:14.586
You were a slave
and so was I.

35:14.586 --> 35:17.723
How do you make peace with
people who bought and sold us?

35:17.723 --> 35:20.492
Who branded us like cattle,
whipped us on Saturday,

35:20.492 --> 35:23.395
then sat in church on Sunday
without a morsel of shame?

35:23.395 --> 35:25.264
Some may keep silent,
Mr. Fortune,

35:25.264 --> 35:26.631
because they tried your way

35:26.631 --> 35:29.272
and they got killed
for their trouble.

35:30.738 --> 35:32.137
I don't mean to scare you,
Miss Scott.

35:32.137 --> 35:33.539
You're only telling
the truth.

35:33.539 --> 35:35.808
But what if you ever stop
playing their game?

35:35.808 --> 35:39.311
If you stop being calm
and keeping the peace?

35:39.311 --> 35:42.547
We are opening the largest
building in Tuskegee.

35:42.547 --> 35:45.384
It will hold offices,
a kitchen,

35:45.384 --> 35:48.454
living space
for students and faculty.

35:48.454 --> 35:50.222
You don't get that
by picking fights.

35:50.222 --> 35:52.258
Well, I think
that the Tuskegee School

35:52.258 --> 35:54.393
is a political argument
in itself.

35:54.393 --> 35:56.996
Can't you see that you both
want the same things?

35:56.996 --> 35:59.731
It's only your methods
that differ.

35:59.731 --> 36:02.268
I just know I'm unwilling
to make nice with people

36:02.268 --> 36:04.240
who'd lynch at will.

36:06.341 --> 36:07.974
Mrs. Washington,
this is delicious.

36:07.974 --> 36:09.141
You have outdone yourself.

36:09.141 --> 36:11.175
Well, thank you.

36:15.283 --> 36:18.554
[birds chirping]
[rooster crows]

36:33.769 --> 36:35.569
Oh.

36:35.569 --> 36:37.203
I'm sorry to wake you so early.

36:37.203 --> 36:38.205
Is something wrong?

36:38.205 --> 36:39.504
No, no.

36:39.504 --> 36:41.140
I just had a thought
last night.

36:41.140 --> 36:43.377
It's about a new angle
for our article.

36:43.377 --> 36:44.343
Well, what is it?

36:44.343 --> 36:46.512
You know,
everyone we've talked to so far

36:46.512 --> 36:48.914
has had to speak
in front of Mr. Washington.

36:48.914 --> 36:49.816
- Mm-hmm.
- What if we speak

36:49.816 --> 36:51.283
to some of the students
without him there

36:51.283 --> 36:52.651
so they can say
what they really think

36:52.651 --> 36:54.720
about what a day at Tuskegee
means to them

36:54.720 --> 36:57.389
and how their education will
affect them later in life.

36:57.389 --> 36:59.459
You see, Miss Scott,
I knew I brought you

36:59.459 --> 37:02.494
down here for a reason.

37:02.494 --> 37:04.731
Well, a student's day
at Tuskegee starts now.

37:04.731 --> 37:07.701
<i>[energetic music]</i>

37:07.701 --> 37:12.939
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:12.939 --> 37:15.945
[lively chatter]

37:17.813 --> 37:19.913
So you all do this
every morning?

37:19.913 --> 37:21.881
Only on the mornings
when we want to eat, sir.

37:21.881 --> 37:23.049
[chuckles]

37:23.049 --> 37:25.284
Is dairy farming
your main study?

37:25.284 --> 37:27.319
We get to do
a bit of everything.

37:27.319 --> 37:29.588
I'm only just back on farming.

37:29.588 --> 37:32.058
Before, I was building the new
dormitory y'all are here for.

37:32.058 --> 37:33.392
You built it yourself?

37:33.392 --> 37:35.061
Me and the other students.

37:35.061 --> 37:36.663
It's part of our masonry class.

37:36.663 --> 37:38.597
So it was
an actual assignment.

37:38.597 --> 37:40.834
Yeah, that's how it tends
to work at the school.

37:40.834 --> 37:42.869
For instance, we plant
the crops in the morning,

37:42.869 --> 37:45.104
and then examine the soil
that afternoon.

37:45.104 --> 37:46.572
[cow moos]
- Oh!

37:46.572 --> 37:48.574
You ain't been
around a cow before?

37:48.574 --> 37:50.542
Not this close.
[laughs nervously]

37:50.542 --> 37:52.145
New Yorkers like
to look at animals,

37:52.145 --> 37:53.745
but they don't touch them much.

37:53.745 --> 37:55.380
Would you like me
to teach you to milk her?

37:55.380 --> 37:57.044
Oh, I don't think so.

37:57.044 --> 37:58.746
We're only here
to write an article.

37:58.746 --> 38:00.352
Go for it, Miss Scott.

38:00.352 --> 38:01.921
When are you ever gonna get
another chance?

38:01.921 --> 38:03.956
Certainly not on 61st Street.

38:03.956 --> 38:06.695
[scoffs]

38:08.296 --> 38:11.430
All right.
[laughs]

38:11.430 --> 38:13.699
So you have to pull
real hard.

38:13.699 --> 38:16.039
Don't worry,
you won't hurt her.

38:18.172 --> 38:19.872
[laughs]

38:19.872 --> 38:21.341
I did it!
[laughs]

38:21.341 --> 38:22.937
You sure did.

38:22.937 --> 38:24.911
Thank you!
What's your name?

38:24.911 --> 38:26.579
David Sturt, ma'am.

38:26.579 --> 38:28.448
Well, thank you, David.
[chuckles]

38:28.448 --> 38:31.988
[indistinct chatter]

38:37.025 --> 38:39.192
You'd never think
a clock had so many pieces.

38:39.192 --> 38:40.492
I would.

38:40.492 --> 38:42.429
Shouldn't you just give it up
and buy a new one?

38:42.429 --> 38:44.097
Oh, you wait.

38:44.097 --> 38:46.265
It may have gone off
during dinner,

38:46.265 --> 38:49.101
but now he knows why,
don't you, Jack?

38:49.101 --> 38:50.603
Is she right, John?

38:50.603 --> 38:52.739
Are you on the track
of the answer?

38:52.739 --> 38:54.539
I think so.

38:54.539 --> 38:57.409
I think the problem is
with the escape wheel,

38:57.409 --> 38:59.078
what they call the escapement.

38:59.078 --> 39:00.279
If the oil is thickening on it,

39:00.279 --> 39:01.714
it could be slowing down
the movement.

39:01.714 --> 39:03.248
You're talking
like a scientist.

39:03.248 --> 39:05.217
He's talking
like a clockmaker,

39:05.217 --> 39:06.753
which is more to the point.

39:06.753 --> 39:08.054
But what can you do about it?

39:08.054 --> 39:09.589
Well, I'm trying
to improve the escape wheel

39:09.589 --> 39:11.557
so it runs without oil.

39:11.557 --> 39:13.993
Good luck with that,
I don't think.

39:13.993 --> 39:15.761
Not so fast.

39:15.761 --> 39:18.734
Let's just be patient
and see how it turns out.

39:20.301 --> 39:21.905
I'm off, my dear.

39:25.373 --> 39:27.006
Well, where are you off to?

39:27.006 --> 39:30.242
I have a fitting at 11:00,
so I'll see you at luncheon.

39:30.242 --> 39:31.644
Before you go,
there's something

39:31.644 --> 39:33.712
I've been meaning to tell you.

39:33.712 --> 39:36.916
I would have said it sooner,
but I didn't want to spoil

39:36.916 --> 39:38.752
the dinner with the Duke.

39:38.752 --> 39:39.585
I'm listening.

39:39.585 --> 39:41.287
Mrs. Astor has asked us

39:41.287 --> 39:43.956
to surrender our box
at the Academy.

39:43.956 --> 39:45.625
What? Why?

39:45.625 --> 39:47.694
Something about
your past career

39:47.694 --> 39:49.328
being too different
for the wives

39:49.328 --> 39:51.096
of the other box holders.

39:51.096 --> 39:52.632
But how did she know that--

39:52.632 --> 39:54.837
How did she know what?

39:56.171 --> 40:00.307
That I worked at one time
as a sort of companion

40:00.307 --> 40:02.274
to Mrs. Russell.

40:02.274 --> 40:04.344
Mrs. George Russell?

40:04.344 --> 40:05.945
I had no money.

40:05.945 --> 40:08.247
I had to survive somehow.

40:08.247 --> 40:09.983
I thought I told you.

40:09.983 --> 40:11.684
Maybe you did.

40:11.684 --> 40:14.786
But what is wrong
with being a companion anyway?

40:14.786 --> 40:17.924
Many ladies of insufficient
means do exactly the same.

40:17.924 --> 40:20.459
Of course they do.

40:20.459 --> 40:22.761
But why did Mrs. Russell
need a companion

40:22.761 --> 40:26.766
when she had her husband
to keep her company?

40:26.766 --> 40:30.469
Well, that was why I left.

40:30.469 --> 40:34.173
I suppose
she must have mentioned it.

40:34.173 --> 40:35.307
But she couldn't have known

40:35.307 --> 40:37.576
Mrs. Astor would react
so badly.

40:37.576 --> 40:42.315
No, she can't have
expected that.

40:42.315 --> 40:44.584
[indistinct chatter]

40:44.584 --> 40:46.419
It was my boyhood dream.

40:46.419 --> 40:47.620
To be a Duke?

40:47.620 --> 40:49.455
More that I wanted
to be king.

40:49.455 --> 40:51.490
Of any particular country?

40:51.490 --> 40:54.026
I hadn't worked out
the details.

40:54.026 --> 40:55.127
I was eight.

40:55.127 --> 40:56.595
[both laugh]

40:56.595 --> 40:59.065
You do make me laugh,
Mr. Van Rhijn.

40:59.065 --> 41:01.300
Oh, how I need that
after a day of contracts

41:01.300 --> 41:03.136
and stock certificates.

41:03.136 --> 41:05.472
My head is spinning.

41:05.472 --> 41:07.907
I hate being a part of it.

41:07.907 --> 41:10.576
I even thought of doing
what you said.

41:10.576 --> 41:13.446
Remind me of my sage advice.

41:13.446 --> 41:15.881
To tell him no.

41:15.881 --> 41:19.555
I just have to summon
the courage to do it.

41:24.560 --> 41:27.293
What if I could help?

41:27.293 --> 41:28.328
How?

41:28.328 --> 41:29.596
I am a banker.

41:29.596 --> 41:31.867
I might be able
to do something.

41:35.938 --> 41:37.470
Murderer!

41:37.470 --> 41:40.676
[crowd yelling]

41:42.877 --> 41:46.845
Are you facing a strike
in Pittsburgh, Mr. Russell?

41:46.845 --> 41:49.215
Will you keep on ignoring
your workers' demands?

41:49.215 --> 41:50.817
Murderer!

41:50.817 --> 41:53.185
You have blood on your hands,
Mr. Russell!

41:53.185 --> 41:56.156
<i>[tense music]</i>

41:56.156 --> 41:58.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:58.958 --> 42:01.761
Why must I be the villain
in every story?

42:01.761 --> 42:03.797
I employ thousands of men.

42:03.797 --> 42:06.599
I have lifted whole towns
out of poverty.

42:06.599 --> 42:07.934
And yet I'm the tyrant

42:07.934 --> 42:10.206
who crushes the faces
of the poor.

42:12.906 --> 42:15.241
I'm told they have a date set
for the strike.

42:15.241 --> 42:17.242
Pinkerton's men say the same.

42:17.242 --> 42:18.443
And it'll be soon.

42:18.443 --> 42:19.712
We're ready
whenever it comes.

42:19.712 --> 42:22.147
We have defenses around
the mills, across the river.

42:22.147 --> 42:24.250
And we have enough scabs
to keep production running.

42:24.250 --> 42:25.718
Let me be clear, Mr. Russell.

42:25.718 --> 42:27.454
The strikers will do
whatever it takes

42:27.454 --> 42:28.855
to keep the scabs out.

42:28.855 --> 42:31.190
The governor has
given me his word.

42:31.190 --> 42:33.893
His militia will get the scabs
into the mills.

42:33.893 --> 42:34.927
We hope.

42:34.927 --> 42:37.964
They won't fight
against armed men.

42:37.964 --> 42:40.269
They will
if they're armed themselves.

42:46.141 --> 42:48.140
Hello.
Mrs. Blane is expecting me.

42:48.140 --> 42:50.476
Thank you.
I can take care of Mr. Russell.

42:50.476 --> 42:52.645
I'm sorry I'm late, but I've
got the carriage right here,

42:52.645 --> 42:55.682
and Mrs. Fish won't mind.

42:55.682 --> 42:56.816
You haven't changed.

42:56.816 --> 42:59.353
I'm not going to the dinner.

42:59.353 --> 43:01.086
What is it?

43:01.086 --> 43:02.856
Are you ill?

43:02.856 --> 43:04.556
And why are we standing
in the doorway?

43:04.556 --> 43:07.527
Can't I come in?
- I'd rather you didn't.

43:07.527 --> 43:09.763
<i>[somber music]</i>

43:09.763 --> 43:11.964
Well, then may I have
an explanation?

43:11.964 --> 43:14.801
I think we should
call a halt.

43:14.801 --> 43:15.968
I don't understand.

43:15.968 --> 43:18.371
We should stop
seeing each other.

43:18.371 --> 43:20.073
No damage has been done,

43:20.073 --> 43:22.208
nothing that won't be forgotten
within a week.

43:22.208 --> 43:25.845
But if we continue as we were,
things might get complicated.

43:25.845 --> 43:27.447
Yes.

43:27.447 --> 43:28.748
They will get complicated

43:28.748 --> 43:30.717
because we're going
to be married

43:30.717 --> 43:31.917
and live together until we die.

43:31.917 --> 43:33.452
Please, Larry,
you're making this

43:33.452 --> 43:34.920
more difficult
than it needs to be.

43:34.920 --> 43:37.424
I think it needs to be
damned difficult.

43:37.424 --> 43:38.858
What prompted it?

43:38.858 --> 43:39.895
Tell me!

43:42.497 --> 43:44.763
Was this because of my mother?

43:44.763 --> 43:46.566
Do you want me to take her on?
Because I will.

43:46.566 --> 43:48.468
Don't.

43:48.468 --> 43:50.402
It won't be any good.

43:50.402 --> 43:53.305
- Then what can I do?
- Nothing.

43:53.305 --> 43:55.442
There's nothing to be done.

43:55.442 --> 43:58.411
We had a fling.

43:58.411 --> 44:00.913
And we enjoyed it.
At least I did.

44:00.913 --> 44:04.316
Now, it's time for us
to move on with our lives.

44:04.316 --> 44:07.687
Here I was thinking
we had a future, but no.

44:07.687 --> 44:09.855
Goodbye, Larry.

44:09.855 --> 44:13.393
Look after yourself,
and please try to be kind

44:13.393 --> 44:16.196
when you think of me.

44:16.196 --> 44:17.397
Wait!

44:17.397 --> 44:24.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:26.708 --> 44:29.643
<i>[choir singing]</i>

44:29.643 --> 44:32.612
[hymnal music]

44:32.612 --> 44:35.749
♪ ♪

44:35.749 --> 44:41.054
all: ♪ For the beauty
of the Earth ♪

44:41.054 --> 44:46.659
♪ For the glory of the skies ♪

44:46.659 --> 44:48.861
[laughs]
I'm sorry.

44:48.861 --> 44:51.864
- For what?
- For laughing in church.

44:51.864 --> 44:54.200
The Lord likes
to see you laugh.

44:54.200 --> 44:55.435
I know I do.

44:55.435 --> 44:58.504
It feels sacrilegious.

44:58.504 --> 45:02.241
I promise you, he won't mind.

45:02.241 --> 45:05.811
Do you know
Mr. and Mrs. Robert Duncan?

45:05.811 --> 45:10.349
They sit about three pews
behind you and your sister.

45:10.349 --> 45:14.388
Do you know where all
of your parishioners sit?

45:14.388 --> 45:16.089
Mostly.

45:16.089 --> 45:18.824
Yes.
[laughs]

45:18.824 --> 45:20.860
What was it you were saying
about the Duncans?

45:20.860 --> 45:23.996
Oh, they offered me their box

45:23.996 --> 45:26.232
for the Academy of Music
next Tuesday.

45:26.232 --> 45:28.234
How generous!

45:28.234 --> 45:30.202
It is generous.

45:30.202 --> 45:32.272
And it makes me feel
like a real New Yorker.

45:32.272 --> 45:35.808
Mm.

45:35.808 --> 45:40.783
I was wondering
if you would like to come.

45:42.184 --> 45:45.652
Goodness.

45:45.652 --> 45:47.954
How kind.

45:47.954 --> 45:49.455
It's to be "Aida."

45:49.455 --> 45:50.956
Have you heard it?

45:50.956 --> 45:54.293
I--I know it's very moving.

45:54.293 --> 45:56.762
It's a love story.

45:56.762 --> 46:00.633
Well, of course,
it's a tragic love story.

46:00.633 --> 46:02.105
Mm.

46:04.906 --> 46:06.205
What do you say?

46:06.205 --> 46:11.444
Well, I ought to check
with Agnes.

46:11.444 --> 46:13.079
But...

46:13.079 --> 46:17.617
♪ To He we raise
this our hymn ♪

46:17.617 --> 46:21.655
I'd love to come.

46:21.655 --> 46:23.993
Thank you very much.

46:26.595 --> 46:27.594
Good.

46:27.594 --> 46:30.563
So I'll collect you at 6:00.

46:30.563 --> 46:32.366
Mm.

46:32.366 --> 46:35.702
<i>[soft music]</i>

46:35.702 --> 46:38.070
Forgive me.

46:38.070 --> 46:41.807
I have another question
to ask you.

46:41.807 --> 46:44.276
- What is it?
- [chuckles]

46:44.276 --> 46:47.380
I was going to ask you
after the opera,

46:47.380 --> 46:50.987
but I can't wait.

46:53.389 --> 46:55.755
What are you--

46:55.755 --> 46:59.359
Will you marry me,
Miss Ada Brook?

46:59.359 --> 47:04.397
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:04.397 --> 47:07.294
- Yes.
- [sighs]

47:07.294 --> 47:11.504
Yes, Mr. Luke Forte.

47:11.504 --> 47:13.373
Yes, I will.

47:13.373 --> 47:20.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:46.474 --> 47:49.909
Please give my compliments
to Mrs. Bauer.

47:49.909 --> 47:52.878
I will, ma'am.

47:52.878 --> 47:55.149
Thank you, Bannister.

47:55.149 --> 48:00.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:00.653 --> 48:03.623
<i>[light music]</i>

48:03.623 --> 48:10.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:12.000 --> 48:13.498
I heard from the Duke.

48:13.498 --> 48:16.102
He says he'll stay with us
when he comes to Newport.

48:16.102 --> 48:17.604
- Really?
- Really.

48:17.604 --> 48:19.371
And you know what it means?

48:19.371 --> 48:21.741
My first event there will be
the talk of the whole town.

48:21.741 --> 48:23.175
We won't have a single refusal

48:23.175 --> 48:25.244
unless people are
at death's door.

48:25.244 --> 48:27.714
And even then, they may
take up their beds and walk.

48:27.714 --> 48:29.548
You've never said
if you liked him.

48:29.548 --> 48:33.019
To be honest, it doesn't take
much to make a Duke likeable.

48:33.019 --> 48:34.654
But yes, I like him.

48:34.654 --> 48:36.022
He's young, unstuffy,

48:36.022 --> 48:38.024
and more polite
than I expected.

48:38.024 --> 48:41.694
And what will Mrs. Winterton
make of all this?

48:41.694 --> 48:43.062
Or don't you care?

48:43.062 --> 48:44.429
Should I care
about the feelings

48:44.429 --> 48:45.865
of a former lady's maid
who attempted

48:45.865 --> 48:49.568
to seduce my husband?

48:49.568 --> 48:52.338
May I find hope in your use
of the word "attempted"?

48:52.338 --> 48:54.641
It was never her claim
that hurt me

48:54.641 --> 48:56.943
but your silence.

48:56.943 --> 48:58.812
Will you forgive me now?

48:58.812 --> 49:02.115
If I do, enjoy it.

49:02.115 --> 49:03.850
There will be
no more forgiveness

49:03.850 --> 49:06.422
if you hide any such thing
from me again.

49:11.527 --> 49:13.960
<i>[soft music]</i>

49:13.960 --> 49:15.629
[sighs]

49:15.629 --> 49:18.631
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:18.631 --> 49:21.668
I've missed you, my darling.

49:21.668 --> 49:24.538
You can't know how much.

49:24.538 --> 49:26.375
I haven't been anywhere.

49:30.011 --> 49:31.611
Oh, yes you have.

49:31.611 --> 49:38.680
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:38.680 --> 49:41.621
<i>[bright music]</i>

49:41.621 --> 49:48.631
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:00.776 --> 50:04.744
Aurora, my dear.
Look at this.

50:04.744 --> 50:06.545
[gasps]

50:06.545 --> 50:08.981
We'd better get
our skates on, Mr. Borden,

50:08.981 --> 50:12.552
if we're to host
the Duke of Buckingham.

50:12.552 --> 50:14.921
Oh, my.

50:14.921 --> 50:16.188
What is it?

50:16.188 --> 50:18.591
Apparently,
Mrs. Russell is to entertain

50:18.591 --> 50:21.428
an English duke
at her home in Newport.

50:21.428 --> 50:22.661
Please.

50:22.661 --> 50:26.466
He is to be the guest
of Mr. and Mrs. George Russell

50:26.466 --> 50:28.000
in Newport.

50:28.000 --> 50:30.837
She's giving a dinner
in his honor.

50:30.837 --> 50:33.072
Perhaps, we'll be invited.

50:33.072 --> 50:36.410
First, she has me
thrown out of the Academy.

50:36.410 --> 50:37.610
And now this?

50:37.610 --> 50:39.646
My dear,
please, don't upset yourself.

50:39.646 --> 50:41.080
I will upset myself.

50:41.080 --> 50:43.149
And I'll upset
Mrs. George Russell

50:43.149 --> 50:45.051
if it's the last thing I do.

50:45.051 --> 50:48.053
Enid, there will be
other dukes.

50:48.053 --> 50:50.657
I don't want other dukes!
I want this duke!

50:50.657 --> 50:53.558
We found him, and he's mine!

50:53.558 --> 50:57.500
But that witch has
stolen him from me!

51:00.335 --> 51:03.403
<i>[spirited orchestral music]</i>

51:03.403 --> 51:10.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:10.572 --> 52:12.541
[bright tone]
